The quantum chemical calculations have shown the optimized structure of the PNCDs with VAL. The complex has a binding energy of 46 kcal/mol. This indicates a strong affinity of the CDs and VAL molecule to bind together and form a stable complex. The binding is dominated by π-π stacking between the aromatic rings of the nano dots and the analyte and three hydrogen bonds: two with the phosphate group and one with the hydroxyl group of the functionalized CDs (indicated in 

                           Fig. S3

                        ). The average intermolecular distance within the complex is less than 3.3 Å. In general, we have seen slight changes in both molecules to maximize the interaction between the rings of the two molecules, which leads to stronger intermolecular interactions.

A reduced density gradient (RDG) analysis has taken place [69] to gain more insight into the binding forces behind the formation of the complex. The hydrogen bonds are represented by blue shadings while the green shadings spreading between the two aromatic systems account for the Van der Waal interactions (π-π stacking) (

                           Fig. S4

                        ).

The Green analytical chemistry (GAC) is an approach that aims to minimize the negative impact of analytical procedures on the environment and human health. The assessment of the greenness of analytical methods is crucial to evaluate and reduce their impact on the environment and analysts [70]. The advantages of using green analytical methods involve improving the quality and reliability of results, enhancing safety and health of analysts and staff, saving costs and resources, and promoting social and environmental responsibility. The proposed method was assessed using the AGREE approach, the pictogram and final score have been generated using the AGREE software. The proposed method scored 0.8 and the closeness of this score to unity indicates that the method is excellent green – with most of the 12 inspected fields having green color (

                           Fig. S5

                        ).
